  "prompt": "I was fired from my job and my boss didn't give me a reason why he fired me. In future job interviews how should I answer why I left my last job?",
  "response": "Here are some professional ways to address this situation:\n\n1. Keep it neutral and professional\n- \"My position was eliminated\"\n- \"The company and I mutually decided to part ways\"\n- \"The job was not the right fit\"\n\n2. Avoid negative language\n- Don't speak poorly of your former employer\n- Don't sound bitter or angry\n- Maintain a calm, professional tone\n\n3. Redirect the conversation\n- Focus on what you learned from the experience\n- Emphasize your skills and what you can bring to the new job\n- Discuss your career goals\n\n4. Be honest if directly asked\n- If they ask specifically about being fired, briefly explain\n- Keep the explanation concise\n- Take responsibility without being overly apologetic\n\n5. Prepare an explanation\n- Practice your response so you sound confident\n- Have a short, clear statement ready\n\nExample script:\n\"While my previous role ended unexpectedly, I'm excited about the opportunities ahead and am committed to contributing my skills to this position.\"\n\nIf the interviewer presses for details, briefly state that you and your employer had different expectations, but don't dwell on it.\n\nRemember: Confidence and professionalism are key when discussing past employment.",
